<!-- Chosen Palette: Custom - "Cool Tech" (#FFFFFF, #F8F9FA, #6C757D, #0D6EFD, #0759d3) -->
<!-- Application Structure Plan: The application is designed as a single-page app with a sticky top navigation bar to facilitate easy access to different stages of the workflow. The structure is thematic: "Configuração" for the one-time setup, "Simulador de Ciclo" for the daily interactive workflow, and "Referência de Comandos" as a quick cheatsheet. This task-oriented design was chosen over a linear document because users have different needs; a beginner might follow it sequentially, while an experienced user might jump directly to the simulator or the command reference. This structure enhances usability by catering to multiple user journeys. -->
<!-- Visualization & Content Choices: 
- Report Info: Initial PC to GitHub setup process. -> Goal: Organize/Inform -> Viz/Presentation: Accordion-style checklist. -> Interaction: Users can click to expand each step, revealing explanations and code snippets with copy buttons. -> Justification: Breaks a long process into manageable chunks, preventing overwhelm and making it easy to follow. -> Library/Method: HTML/Tailwind/JS.
- Report Info: The daily sync cycle (pull, work, add, commit, push). -> Goal: Organize/Change -> Viz/Presentation: Interactive diagram with three columns (PC, GitHub, Notebook). -> Interaction: Buttons for "PULL" and "PUSH" trigger animations that visually move a "file" element between the columns, with accompanying text explaining the state change. -> Justification: This transforms the most critical and abstract concept of the guide into a tangible, memorable visual process. -> Library/Method: HTML/Tailwind/JS.
- Report Info: All terminal commands. -> Goal: Inform -> Viz/Presentation: A clean list of code blocks. -> Interaction: Each code block has a click-to-copy button. -> Justification: Provides a high-utility feature that streamlines the actual execution of the commands for the user. -> Library/Method: HTML/Tailwind/JS.
- CONFIRMATION: No charts were needed as the content is procedural, not data-driven. The focus is on interactive process diagrams. -->
<!-- CONFIRMATION: NO SVG graphics used. NO Mermaid JS used. -->
